\part{Phonology}

\chapter{Types of sounds}

\section{Consonants}

Danetian has 20 consonant phonemes: six plosives, six fricatives, two
affricates, and six sonorants. These phonemes are organized in the table
below.

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{l|cccc}
	\toprule
	~ & Labial & Dental & Palatal & Velar \\
	\midrule
	Plosive & \ipa{p~b} & \ipa{t~d} & ~ & \ipa{k~g} \\
	Affricate & ~ & ~ & \ipa{tʃ~dʒ} & ~ \\
	Fricative & \ipa{f~v} & \ipa{s~z} & \ipa{ʃ} & \ipa{x} \\
	Nasal & \ipa{m} & \ipa{n} & \ipa{ɲ} & ~ \\
	Rhotic & ~ & \ipa{r} & ~ & ~ \\
	Approximant & ~ & \ipa{l} & \ipa{j} & ~ \\
	\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

The main dialect of Danetian has several allophonical variations for
consonants, summarized below. However, the reader is encouraged to speak the
language with their own regional accent, and to pronounce words in whichever
way feels more natural to them. The points below are intended as a guideline,
and are not strictly authoritative.
\begin{itemize}
	\item Whenver \ipa{/s/} appears between vowels or before a voiced
		consonant, it is pronounced as \ipa{[z]}:
		\subitem \lan{nefesos} \ipa{['nɛ.fɛ.zos]} \qt{of the cloud}
		\subitem \lan{fesor} \ipa{[fɛ'zor]} \qt{hand}
		\subitem \lan{tusontis} \ipa{['tu.zon.tis]} \qt{thousand}
		\subitem \lan{esvos} \ipa{['ɛz.vos]} \qt{horse}
		\subitem \lan{donvos} \ipa{['don.vos]} \qt{number}
	\item \ipa{/r/} is pronounced as \ipa{[r]} by default, but as \ipa{[ɾ]}
		between vowels:
		\subitem \lan{pater} \ipa{[pa'tɛr]} \qt{father}
		\subitem \lan{kruros} \ipa{['kru.ɾos]} \qt{bloody}
	\item \ipa{/l/} is pronounced as \ipa{[l]} by default, but as \ipa{[ɫ]}
		at the end of a word, before a consonant, or before \ipa{/o/}
		or \ipa{/u/}:
		\subitem \lan{lana} \ipa{['la.na]} \qt{wool},
		\subitem \lan{luvos} \ipa{['ɫu.vos]} \qt{love},
		\subitem \lan{lokus} \ipa{['ɫo.kus]} \qt{lake},
		\subitem \lan{Michael} \ipa{[mi.xa'ɛɫ]} \qt{Michael},
		\subitem \lan{Vilmos} \ipa{['viɫ.mos]} \qt{William}.
	\item \ipa{/x/} is pronounced as \ipa{[x~h]}.
\end{itemize}

\section{Vowels}

Like many other languages around the world, Danetian has five vowel phonemes.
There is no vowel length distinction.

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{l|ccc}
	\toprule
	~ & Front & Central & Back \\
	\midrule
	Close & i & ~ & u \\
	Mid & e & ~ & o \\
	Open & ~ & a & ~ \\
	\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

The vowels \ipa{/a~e~o/} can also be combined with \ipa{/i~u/} to form the
following falling diphthongs:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{c|cc}
	\toprule
	~ & \ipa{i} & \ipa{u} \\
	\midrule
	\ipa{a} & \ipa{ai̯} & \ipa{au̯} \\
	\ipa{e} & \ipa{ei̯} & \ipa{eu̯} \\
	\ipa{o} & \ipa{oi̯} & ~ \\
	\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

In the main dialect of Danetian, vowels undergo a couple of allophonical
variations. Once again, each speaker will have their own unique pronounciation
based on their regional accent, so the following points are merely a guideline.
\begin{itemize}
	\item \ipa{/e/} is pronounced as \ipa{[ɛ]} by default, but as \ipa{[e]}
		whenever the following syllable contains \ipa{/i/} or
		\ipa{/j/}:
		\subitem \lan{preseti} \ipa{['prɛ.ze.ti]} \qt{he asks}
		\subitem \lan{kreva} \ipa{['krɛ.va]} \qt{raw blood}
		\subitem \lan{drageti} \ipa{['dra.ge.ti]} \qt{he drags}
	\item \ipa{/o/} is always pronounced as \ipa{[o]}.
\end{itemize}

