\chapter{Numerals}

\section{Cardinals}

Cardinals are used for counting things: \textit{one}, \textit{two},
\textit{three}, \textit{four}... They can be simple, like \textit{twenty},
or compound, like \textit{four hundred}. A cardinal number governs a noun or
a noun phrase, forming a numeral phrase as a whole.

\begin{exe}
	\ex
	\gll
	\lan{trifi}
	\lan{berdantifi}
	\lan{virois} \\
	three-{\Ins} tall-{\Ins}-{\Pl} men-{\Ins}-{\Pl} \\
	\glt \qt{with the three tall men}
\end{exe}

\begin{exe}
	\ex
	\gll
	\lan{nevandsont}
	\lan{pempe}
	\lan{thesióm}
	\lan{Martines}
	\lan{Lutheres} \\
	ninety five theses-{\Gen}-{\Pl} Martin-{\Gen} Luther-{\Gen} \\
	\glt \qt{the ninety five theses of Martin Luther}
\end{exe}

\begin{exe}
	\ex
	\gll
	\lan{tusontis}
	\lan{petvóres}
	\lan{satones}
	\lan{octodesam}
	\lan{pavenjóm}
	\lan{dinóm}
	\lan{i}
	\lan{neptóm}
	\lan{Medanosjo}
	\lan{Patriotiskosjo}
	\lan{Urusjes} \\
	thousand four hundred eighteen fiery-{\Gen}-{\Pl}
	days-{\Gen}-{\Pl} and nights-{\Gen}-{\Pl}
	Great-{\Gen} Patriotic-{\Gen} War-{\Gen} \\
	\glt \qt{one thousand four hundred and eighteen fiery days and nights
	of the Great Patriotic War}
\end{exe}

