\section{Compound numerals}

Several simple numerals can be arranged to form a compound numeral. In English,
an example of this would be \textit{sixty nine}, or \textit{four hundred and
twenty}. We can also do this in Danetian:
\begin{multicols}{2}
\begin{itemize}
	\item 21: \lan{vidsant oinos}
	\item 42: \lan{petvardsont dvo}
	\item 69: \lan{svedsont nevan}
	\item 96: \lan{nevandsont sveks}
	\item 101: \lan{satón oinos}
	\item 144: \lan{satón petvardsont petvóres}
	\item 200: \lan{dvo satones}
	\item 210: \lan{dvo satones desam}
	\item 365: \lan{tres satones svedsont pempe}
	\item 420: \lan{petvóres satones vidsant}
	\item 500: \lan{pempe satonóm}
	\item 507: \lan{pempe satonóm septam}
	\item 1001: \lan{tusontis oinos}
	\item 1200: \lan{tusontis dvo satones}
	\item 1418: \lan{tusontis petvóres satones octodesam}
	\item 1999: \lan{tusontis nevan satones nevandsont nevan}
	\item 2000: \lan{dvo tusonties}
	\item 2021: \lan{dvo tusonties vidsant oinos}
	\item 3000: \lan{tres tusonties}
	\item 5000: \lan{pempe tusontióm}
	\item 9999: \lan{nevan tusontióm nevan satonóm nevandsont nevan}
\end{itemize}
\end{multicols}

Notice that a numeral can govern another numeral, as in \textit{two thousand}.
In this case, the subordinate numeral follows the case agreement rules
discussed in section \ref{sec:case-agreement-for-simple-cardinals}. The
gender of this subordinate numeral is assumed to be masculine.

\chapter{Pronouns and pro-adverbs}

\section{Personal pronouns}
