\section{Copula omission}
\label{sec:copula-omission}

The copula can be optionally omitted if it is in the present tense.
\begin{itemize}
	\item \lan{Aicaterina en Gallí.}
		(Catherine [is] in France).
	\item \lan{Petros mechaniskos insjenier.}
		(Peter [is] a mechanical engineer).
	\item \lan{Nestor i Antonios physicoi.}
		(Nestor and Anthony [are] physicists).
	\item \lan{Benjamín viros, de Alexandra bena.}
		(Benjamin [is] a man, and Alexandra [is] a woman).
\end{itemize}

If it's not in the present tense, then the copula can still be omitted,
provided that it was used in the same tense in a previous sentence. This way,
the tense of the copula is understood from context.
\begin{itemize}
	\item \lan{En prameni but Verdom, da Verdom opi Divosjo, da Divos
		Verdom.}
		(In the beginning was the Word, and the Word [was] with God,
		and the Word [was] God).
\end{itemize}



\section{Possession}

Unlike most European languages, Danetian does not typically use a verb
\textit{to have} to express possession. Rather, it uses a grammatical
construction: Possessor-{\Dat} copula object-{\Nom}.
\begin{itemize}
	\item Medjo iti estin rufra automobilis.
		(I will have a red car).
	\item Petroi i Nestorei esti bibliom physicas.
		(Peter and Nestor have a physics book).
	\item Aicaterinai bunt tres bles.
		(Catherine had three apples).
\end{itemize}

Of course, the copula can also be omitted according to the rules in section
\ref{sec:copula-omission}.

